        </p>
        <p>
          Yellow fever epidemics swept through Key West in 1853, 1862, 1867, and periodically into the 1890s. Fort East Martello, built by the Union Army during the Civil War, doubled as a fever hospital where soldiers died faster from mosquito-borne disease than from any Confederate threat. The Key West Cemetery, established in 1847 after a hurricane washed coffins from the original burial ground, holds an estimated 100,000 burials on just 19 acres‚Äîmore dead than the island's living population.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
